        <section>
            <section.front>
                <doc.title toc-guid="I94cbf039e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335">
                    <head parent="doc.title">
                        <bop/>
                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>§</label.name>
                        <label.designator>3:2.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>Transfer for pretrial proceedings only</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>With one statutory exception, the Panel is only authorized to transfer cases for pretrial
                        proceedings.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022c1d40680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">1</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        cannot transfer a case for trial, nor can it consider any motions concerning venue or dismissal
                        related to the place of venue.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The statute contemplates that actions be transferred and consolidated by the Panel for
                        pretrial proceedings and that they be remanded by the Panel for trial.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In practice, remand frequently does not take place.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022d07a0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">2</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>A report on complex litigation by the American Law Institute recommends that the power of
                        the Panel be expanded to include trial as well as pretrial proceedings.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022df200680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">3</footnote.reference>] This ALI
                        project report has met with a somewhat indeterminate fate in the courts and in the academic
                        community.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>It has not yet had any significant impact on the handling of complex cases.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022df201680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">4</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The ALI report reflects a clear judgment in favor of expanded use of proceedings before
                        the Panel to manage complex federal court litigation.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Additionally, it includes proposals to expand the ability of the courts to coordinate
                        state court cases[<footnote.reference refid="I022e1910680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">
                            5</footnote.reference>] and parallel cases pending in state and federal courts.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022e1911680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">6</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>Many actions are not remanded because they are either settled or disposed of on motion in
                        the transferee court.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Additionally, for many years, the transferee court would consider a motion to transfer
                        venue under <cite.query w-src-number="0304913950" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1404" w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                ID="I0cdd7ff0680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">28 U.S.C.A. §
                            1404(a)</cite.query>, and frequently transfer actions to itself for trial.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022e1912680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">7</footnote.reference>]
                        Self-transfer under <cite.query w-src-number="0304913950" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                        w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1404" w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                        ID="I0ce17794680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">§ 1404(a)
                        </cite.query> was ended by the Supreme Court decision in <cite.query w-src-number="0304913950"
                                                                                             w-serial-number="1998061318"
                                                                                             w-seq-number="00007"
                                                                                             w-ref-type="RS"
                                                                                             w-pub-number="0000708"
                                                                                             ID="I0ce17792680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">
                            Lexecon
                        </cite.query> in 1998, although efforts to restore it in Congress continue.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022e4020680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">8</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>One consequence of the Supreme Court&apos;s
                        <cite.query w-src-number="0304913950" w-serial-number="1998061318" w-seq-number="00009"
                                    w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I0ce32542680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">
                            <ital>Lexecon</ital>
                        </cite.query>
                        prohibition on self-transfer is the recognition that transfer for all purposes under <cite.query
                                w-src-number="0304913950" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1404" w-pub-number="1000546"
                                ID="I0ce32544680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">28 U.S.C.A. § 1404(a)
                        </cite.query> may be preferable to transfer by the Panel.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel itself has recognized this advantage as a reason to deny or defer
                        centralization.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022e4021680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">9</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        has also recognized that a transfer under <cite.query w-src-number="0304913950"
                                                                              w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                                              w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1404"
                                                                              w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                                              ID="I0ce76b00680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">
                            section 1404(a)
                        </cite.query> may destroy the multidistrict nature of the litigation, es-<?pagebreak label="22"?>sentially mooting any
                        consideration of transfer under section 1407.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022e6730680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">10</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>In the post-Lexecon era, courts have looked to other means to facilitate trial in the
                        transferee court when it serves the interests of the parties.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>One mechanism for accomplishing this is for the parties to agree to trial in the
                        transferee court.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022e6731680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">11</footnote.reference>] Some
                        courts held that parties to an action could consent to transfer of the actions to the transferee
                        judge for trial.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I022e6732680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">12</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
